        <p>Whether you realize it or not, Generative AI has already become deeply woven into many of the tools and platforms you use every day. From chatbots on retail websites to the AI-generated summaries now appearing at the top of Google searches (a result of its own LLM, Gemini), this technology is no longer something you have to seek out, it‚Äôs baked into the digital spaces you already navigate.</p>
        <p>This quiet integration means that AI is influencing how we search for information, interact with services, and even make decisions, often without us fully noticing. As this technology becomes more embedded in everything from search engines to productivity software, it‚Äôs important to recognize both its potential and its limitations. While it can speed things up or offer new ways to approach a task, it also shapes what we see, how we solve problems, and which voices get amplified.</p>
        <p>In computing specifically, AI shows up in a range of roles, not just as a flashy tool for generating text or images, but as something that can impact how we code, debug, research, and even learn. It‚Äôs becoming a common layer across tools students and developers rely on. That makes it all the more important to not only learn how to use AI effectively, but to critically engage with how it works, what assumptions it carries, and when to question its output.</p>
        <p>As AI becomes more embedded in everyday tech, it‚Äôs no longer just a specialized tool for experts, it‚Äôs something students, creatives, and developers are already expected to navigate. Whether you‚Äôre aware of it or not, you‚Äôre entering an academic and professional world where knowing how to work with AI is becoming just as important as knowing how to work without it.</p>

        <p>So what does that actually look like in practice?</p>
        <p>Here are a few ways you might start to interact with AI in your daily work and some things to keep in mind as you do:</p>

