      <h3 class="subtitle">Using AI for Coding Help</h3>
      <p>For many students in computing and engineering, the first major use of AI is as a coding assistant. Tools like GitHub Copilot, ChatGPT, and Replit Ghostwriter can:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Suggest code snippets based on comments or patterns.</li>
        <li>Help debug errors when you're stuck.</li>
        <li>Scaffold basic functions or templates to get you moving faster.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>When used carefully, these tools can speed up your development process, help you learn new languages or frameworks, and even make solo projects more manageable. Just remember: the goal is to understand what you‚Äôre building, not just paste what the AI suggests. If you ever find yourself accepting code you don‚Äôt fully understand, that‚Äôs a good signal to slow down and dig deeper.</p>

      <hr>

      <h3 class="subtitle">Using AI for Study Tools</h3>
      <p>Keeping up with multiple classes, assignments, and exams can get overwhelming fast. AI-powered study tools can help lighten the mental load by:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Generating flashcards from your notes (Quizlet AI).</li>
        <li>Helping explain tricky homework questions (Socratic).</li>
        <li>Organizing study schedules or creating mock quizzes (ChatGPT custom prompts).</li>
      </ul>
      <p>These tools don‚Äôt replace studying, but they can streamline how you prepare, helping you focus your energy where it‚Äôs most needed. And again, it‚Äôs important to verify: AI-generated study materials sometimes oversimplify or miss nuance, especially in complex subjects.</p>

      <hr>

      <h3 class="subtitle">Using AI for Brainstorming and Creative Work</h3>
      <p>Whether you're writing an essay, designing an app, or planning a group project, getting started is often the hardest part. This is where AI can really shine:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Brainstorming possible angles for a paper or presentation.</li>
        <li>Outlining project ideas.</li>
        <li>Suggesting creative approaches you hadn‚Äôt considered.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Tools like ChatGPT, Claude, Gemini, or specialized writing tools like Notion AI and Sudowrite can act like a thought partner, someone to bounce early ideas off of without the pressure of needing perfection. The important thing to remember is that AI is good at sparking ideas, but the real creativity, analysis, and critical thinking still have to come from you.</p>

      <hr>

      <h3 class="subtitle">Using AI for Research Support</h3>
      <p>Starting a big research project can feel like standing at the edge of a giant maze. AI tools like Elicit, Consensus, and Scite can help you:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Find relevant academic papers.</li>
        <li>Summarize large bodies of research quickly.</li>
        <li>See how different studies connect and evolve over time.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Used well, these tools can shorten the time it takes to get oriented on a topic and make it easier to spot promising directions for deeper research. But like with all AI outputs: don't take summaries at face value. Always check sources directly, especially if you're using information in academic work.</p>

      <hr>

      <h3 class="subtitle">Using AI for Organization and Productivity</h3>
      <p>Not every use of AI has to be flashy. Sometimes the most powerful thing AI can do for you is make it easier to manage your time and energy. Tools like Notion AI, Trello AI assistants, and even structured ChatGPT prompts can help:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Break down large assignments into smaller, manageable steps.</li>
        <li>Build checklists or timelines for long-term projects.</li>
        <li>Prioritize tasks when everything feels overwhelming.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Used thoughtfully, AI can help you stay more focused and strategic, without feeling like you‚Äôre constantly scrambling.</p>

      <br><br>
      <p>The bottom line:</p>
      <p><strong> AI isn‚Äôt here to replace your skills, it‚Äôs here to assist them.</strong></p>
      <p> By choosing tools thoughtfully, setting clear goals, and staying critical about what AI suggests, you can build a workflow that‚Äôs not just faster, but smarter.</p>
      <p>You don‚Äôt need to use everything. Start with one or two tools that match your real needs, and grow from there.</p>

